Exercise 1: Basic getElementById Manipulation
Objective: Change the text of an HTML element using getElementById.
HTML:
html
Copier le code
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Exercise 1</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1 id="header">Original Text</h1>
    <button onclick="changeText()">Change Text</button>

    <script>
        function changeText() {
            var header = document.getElementById("header");
            header.innerHTML = "New Text";
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
Task: Modify the text of the header when the button is clicked.
Exercise 2: Drawing on Canvas
Objective: Draw a rectangle on a canvas element.
HTML:
html
Copier le code
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Exercise 2</title>
</head>
<body>
    <canvas id="myCanvas" width="200" height="100" style="border:1px solid #000000;"></canvas>

    <script>
        function drawRectangle() {
            var canvas = document.getElementById("myCanvas");
            var ctx = canvas.getContext("2d");
            ctx.fillStyle = "#FF0000";
            ctx.fillRect(20, 20, 150, 100);
        }
        drawRectangle();
    </script>
</body>
</html>
Task: Draw a red rectangle on the canvas.
Exercise 3: Using document.querySelector()
Objective: Change the style of an element using document.querySelector().
HTML:
html
Copier le code
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Exercise 3</title>
    <style>
        .myClass {
            color: blue;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <p class="myClass">This is a paragraph.</p>
    <button onclick="changeColor()">Change Color</button>

    <script>
        function changeColor() {
            var paragraph = document.querySelector(".myClass");
            paragraph.style.color = "red";
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
Task: Change the color of the paragraph to red when the button is clicked.
Exercise 4: Drawing a Circle on Canvas
Objective: Draw a circle on a canvas element.
HTML:
html
Copier le code
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Exercise 4</title>
</head>
<body>
    <canvas id="myCanvas" width="200" height="200" style="border:1px solid #000000;"></canvas>

    <script>
        function drawCircle() {
            var canvas = document.getElementById("myCanvas");
            var ctx = canvas.getContext("2d");
            ctx.beginPath();
            ctx.arc(100, 100, 50, 0, 2 * Math.PI);
            ctx.stroke();
        }
        drawCircle();
    </script>
</body>
</html>
Task: Draw a circle in the center of the canvas.
Exercise 5: Dynamic Content Creation
Objective: Add new elements to the DOM using JavaScript.
HTML:
html
Copier le code
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Exercise 5</title>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="container"></div>
    <button onclick="addElement()">Add Element</button>

    <script>
        function addElement() {
            var newDiv = document.createElement("div");
            newDiv.innerHTML = "I am a new div!";
            document.getElementById("container").appendChild(newDiv);
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
Task: Add a new <div> element to the container each time the button is clicked.
Exercise 6: Interactive Canvas Drawing
Objective: Draw a rectangle on the canvas where the user clicks.
HTML:
html
Copier le code
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Exercise 6</title>
</head>
<body>
    <canvas id="myCanvas" width="400" height="400" style="border:1px solid #000000;"></canvas>

    <script>
        var canvas = document.getElementById("myCanvas");
        var ctx = canvas.getContext("2d");

        canvas.addEventListener("click", function(event) {
            var rect = canvas.getBoundingClientRect();
            var x = event.clientX - rect.left;
            var y = event.clientY - rect.top;
            ctx.fillStyle = "#00FF00";
            ctx.fillRect(x, y, 50, 50);
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
Task: Draw a green rectangle at the position where the user clicks on the canvas.
These exercises cover basic and slightly advanced DOM manipulation, interaction with canvas, and using selectors. Each exercise builds on fundamental concepts that are crucial for web development.
